“Please!” Queen Elwin begged, “Don't send her away! She's just a child!” The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with royal advisors standing by. The queen gave birth to a girl. The mere thought of this made the Ice King furrow his brow.
The infant looked just like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair, with a few strands of blue hair sprinkled in. The Ice King thought having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only sons before.
“You have two choices: either kill this child or abandon her in the wilderness. Elwin, this is your punishment.” He spat out her name like poison, as he always did.
The Kingdom of Frost was not always a kingdom. It was once divided into two parts: the northern part was a non-magical kingdom, while the southern part was a kingdom full of magical powers. Due to the northern part's greed, the two kingdoms engaged in endless wars until the southern part proposed a ceasefire.
When the southern part was in despair, members of the royal family were willing to sacrifice everything to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed that the only princess be married to the prince of the north, become the queen of the north, and give birth to a son as the future king. After that, the south would merge with the north, and a unified kingdom would be established. The north accepted this proposal, and Princess Elwin married Prince Akur.
“Please, my king, for the safety of my child, you can do anything to me – imprison me, exile me, even kill me.” Queen Elwin begged, holding the child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at the queen, his eyes filled with disgust. Perhaps, just perhaps, he would have some pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him in his darkest moments, and borne him children.
“Okay. The child can stay in the palace.” The queen breathed a sigh of relief when she heard the Ice King's words. “But,” he added, “you will be executed.”
The royal advisors and Queen Elwin both showed expressions of terror. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. “Yes, my king,” she bowed her head.
The Ice King ordered royal advisors to take the queen's daughter to an empty room in Elwin. After that, he ordered guards to take Elwin to a public execution site where everyone could see.
When the guards took her to the execution site, the citizens saw their only queen – and the kindest queen – about to be executed, and they were very angry. Some people cried, some shouted and tried to attack the guards, and some wondered why this was happening; but they all had the same question.
“Let her go!”
“Why are they treating her this way?”
When Elwin approached the wooden pole, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner of fire. The former queen Elwin would be burned alive. No one should be executed by fire, not even a criminal. In the Ice Kingdom, fire execution is the cruelest punishment.
Elwin was tied to the wooden pole, and the king began to tell the story of how the queen betrayed them all. The people of the Ice Kingdom refused to believe and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the pole, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
“Carly, live on!” Elwin the queen's life came to an end here.
The hall was silent
In the south wing of this cold palace, an endless “tick-tock” sound came from the leftmost room. Former servants were always curious about what was inside, but they were too afraid to get close. The maids were walking around the hall, whispering to each other, spreading various rumors. Some people believed that the Ice King's late wife Elwin was living in this room, waiting to be released.
They were completely wrong. Avery walked towards the south wing, thinking to himself, while the servants walked along the wall, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there were many rumors about him, as he was the only one allowed to enter the room.
He knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you in there?" Elwin whispered against the complex door, adorned with snowflakes and crown patterns, which were the symbols of the royal family.
He didn't know if she would let him in this time, unlike before. I still have the bruises from last time, Elwin remembered, and couldn't help but laugh. At that time, Carly threw a book at him, but when she saw who it was, she immediately apologized.
A soft sound came from inside the room, as if she was saying she couldn't go anywhere and was right there.
"Can I come in?" Elwin asked, remembering the consequences of his previous uninvited entry.
The room fell silent again, with a faint sound echoing, as if saying "come in". Aferri felt a chill run down his spine, unsure if it was due to the cold or the voice. Although Aferri had been there for many years, hearing the sound from the room still felt a bit strange.
"I'm in," Aferri said slowly opening the door. From a normal person's perspective, the scene inside the room was unusual, but it was also somewhat expected. The room was filled with paper, books scattered everywhere, a broken table, and many ice sculptures. There were no windows, and the room was almost dark. It was also colder than other parts of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked like it had been hit by a blizzard, with everything in disarray.
The girl in the room was curled up on the bed, wrapped in a blanket, reading a notebook. A small lantern lit up the room.
"What notebook are you reading?" Aferri sat down beside Karli's bed and asked.
